The Project StructureImagine your files are organized like this on your machine:Plaintext/home/mantra/work/mikshi_box/                <-- The Project Root
├── CMakeLists.txt                          (Parent CMake)
├── libs/
│   └── json.hpp                            (The file we want)
└── source/
    └── MxService/
        └── CMakeLists.txt                  (Child CMake)
Option A: Absolute (Top-Down)

set(LIBS_PATH "${CMAKE_SOURCE_DIR}/libs")

    Pros: Clean and easy to read. No need to count ../ dots.

    Cons: Breaks if you copy the MxService folder into a different project that doesn't have a libs folder at its root.

Option B: Relative (Local View)

set(LIBS_PATH "${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR}/../../libs")

    Pros: Portable. You can move the entire project folder anywhere, and the relative distance between files stays the same.

    Cons: Breaks if you move the MxService folder deeper (e.g., to source/interns/sugam/MxService). The ../../ math will no longer reach the root.

Summary Rule

    Use CMAKE_SOURCE_DIR for shared project-wide folders (like your libs). It prevents path calculation errors.

    Use CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR only when you need to find files that live inside the same folder as your CMakeLists.txt.
